    name: "White Water Rafting Seti River Pokhara",
    category: "ADVENTURE_SPORTS",
    summary: "The Upper Seti River offers one of Nepal's most accessible white-water rafting adventures, with Grade III\u2013IV rapids on a glacially fed river just 30 minutes from Pokhara Lakeside. The half-day trip covers approximately 8 km of exciting water, including powerful rapids and calm stretches with views of the Annapurna foothills. The river originates in the Annapurna snowfields, making it clear and cold throughout the year with a distinctive milky-turquoise colour.",
    story: `<p>The Seti River — whose name means 'white' in Nepali, a reference to its distinctive milky-blue glacier-fed waters — provides Pokhara's resident adventure scene with one of its most exciting products. The Upper Seti rafting trip launches from the Hemja put-in point north of Pokhara, where the river tumbles out of its gorge and enters a more accessible stretch of powerful rapids. The water is fed directly from the snowfields of the Annapurna range, making it strikingly clear and cold, and the surrounding gorge walls of limestone and schist are draped in subtropical vegetation, creating a beautiful natural corridor entirely separate from the busy tourist scene of Lakeside.</p><p>The rapids on the upper section include several genuine Class III and IV features — hydraulic stoppers, pour-overs, and technical lines that require experienced guiding and proper safety equipment. Between rapids, the river calms into deep green pools and gently braided channels where trekkers can leap from rocks and simply float. Because the trip is a half-day experience starting in the morning, it integrates easily into a broader Pokhara itinerary alongside paragliding, kayaking, or a Phewa Lake sunset. All reputable operators provide helmets, life jackets, wetsuits where necessary, and a safety kayaker accompanying each raft.</p><p>Beyond the adrenaline, the Seti River offers something rarer — a chance to experience the raw Himalayan watershed landscape up close, far from the mountain-view restaurants and tourist shops of Lakeside. The gorge section near Hemja reveals natural limestone caves and eroded cliffs that the river has carved over millennia. The Lower Seti, which flows through the city of Pokhara itself and famously disappears underground in several places, is a gentler alternative suited to families and beginners. Together, the upper and lower sections make Pokhara a compelling hub for river adventure at multiple skill levels.</p><ul><li>Grade III–IV rapids on glacially fed turquoise waters</li><li>Half-day adventure, easily combined with other Pokhara activities</li><li>Gorge scenery with limestone cliffs and subtropical vegetation</li><li>Annapurna mountain views from the river valley</li><li>Suitable for adventurous beginners with guide assistance</li></ul>`,
