    category: "TREK_ROUTE",
    summary: "The Everest Base Camp Trek is the world's most famous trekking route, leading through Sherpa villages, Buddhist monasteries, and high-altitude wilderness to the foot of the world's highest mountain at 5,364 m. The classic 14-day round trip from Lukla passes through Namche Bazaar, Tengboche, Dingboche, and Gorakshep, with most trekkers also ascending Kala Patthar (5,643 m) for the definitive close-up view of Everest. The route is a UNESCO World Heritage journey through the heart of the Khumbu region.",
    story: `<p>No trekking route on earth carries the weight of legend that the Everest Base Camp trail does. The journey begins with the notoriously exciting landing at Lukla's Tenzing-Hillary Airport (2,840 m), where the short runway ends abruptly at a cliff and begins the story. From Lukla, the trail descends to the Dudh Koshi River and follows it north through the rhododendron and juniper forests of Phakding, crossing a series of suspension bridges festooned with prayer flags before the steep ascent to Namche Bazaar at 3,440 m — the de facto capital of the Khumbu Sherpas and gateway to the Everest region. The first acclimatisation day in Namche typically includes a hike to the Everest View Hotel (3,880 m) for the first proper glimpse of Everest above the ridge.</p><p>Above Namche, the trail enters the Sagarmatha National Park's high-altitude wilderness, passing through the monastery village of Tengboche (3,860 m), where the morning chanting of monks and the sight of Everest, Lhotse, and Ama Dablam from the monastery courtyard constitutes one of the Himalaya's great experiences. Further up through Dingboche and Lobuche, the landscape becomes increasingly stark and beautiful — yak caravans plod along moraine paths, and the peaks grow impossibly close. Gorakshep (5,164 m), the last settlement, serves as the base for the final push to Everest Base Camp through the lateral moraine of the Khumbu Glacier.</p><p>Everest Base Camp at 5,364 m is a surprisingly humble destination — a jumble of tents and prayer flags on the glacier, with Everest's summit pyramid visible over the Khumbu Icefall above. But the emotional weight of arriving here, having walked the same path as Hillary, Tenzing, and countless subsequent mountaineers, is profound. Most trekkers rise early the following morning for the steep 500 m ascent to Kala Patthar (5,643 m) for the unobstructed Everest sunrise view before descending to Lukla over two days. The journey remains one of humanity's great walks — a physical, cultural, and spiritual immersion like no other.</p><ul><li>Everest Base Camp at 5,364 m on the Khumbu Glacier</li><li>Kala Patthar (5,643 m) — best close-up Everest sunrise viewpoint</li><li>Tengboche Monastery prayers at dawn with Everest backdrop</li><li>Namche Bazaar — vibrant Sherpa cultural hub and acclimatisation stop</li><li>Suspension bridges, prayer flags, and yak caravans of the Khumbu valley</li><li>UNESCO Sagarmatha National Park high-altitude wilderness</li></ul>`,
