    name: "Island Peak (Imja Tse)",
    category: "TREK_ROUTE",
    summary: "Island Peak (Imja Tse, 6,189 m) is one of Nepal's most popular trekking peaks, named in 1953 by the British Everest expedition for its appearance as an island surrounded by glaciers when viewed from Dingboche. Located above Chukung in the shadow of Lhotse's massive south face, the climb combines a superb high-altitude approach through the heart of the Khumbu with a genuine mountaineering challenge on a glaciated summit ridge. It is commonly combined with the Everest Base Camp trek.",
    story: `<p>Island Peak was christened by the 1953 British Everest expedition — from their vantage point at Dingboche, the peak's dark rocky mass appeared to float as an island in a sea of surrounding glaciers, a visual impression that remains accurate today. The mountain's technical name, Imja Tse, references the Imja River that drains the valley below. Situated just north of the growing Imja Glacial Lake (one of the world's most closely monitored glacial lakes for outburst flood risk) and beneath the towering south face of Lhotse (8,516 m), Island Peak occupies some of the most dramatic glacial topography in the Khumbu.</p><p>The approach to Island Peak from Lukla typically takes 10–12 days, following the classic EBC route through Namche, Tengboche, and Dingboche before branching east to Chukung (4,730 m). From Chukung, a further half-day walk reaches Island Peak Base Camp (5,100 m) and high camp (5,600 m). The summit push involves a predawn start, crossing a broad glacier and navigating a fixed-rope section on the final 55-degree ice headwall below the summit ridge. This headwall — the crux of the route — requires competent crampon technique and comfort with exposure but is within the reach of most physically fit and mentally determined trekkers who have spent adequate time acclimatising.</p><p>From the summit ridge at 6,189 m, the view is breathtaking — Lhotse's enormous south face fills the northern sky, while Makalu, Baruntse, Ama Dablam, and the Khumbu ranges extend in every direction. The summit is a narrow ice ridge with significant drops on either side, requiring care but offering a magnificent high-altitude experience that few non-mountaineers ever attain. Island Peak is frequently combined with an EBC trek to create a comprehensive 20-day Khumbu adventure that includes Base Camp, Kala Patthar, and a genuine summit above 6,000 m — a package that represents one of the finest mountain journeys available anywhere in the world.</p><ul><li>Summit at 6,189 m with views of Lhotse, Makalu, Ama Dablam, and Baruntse</li><li>Technical ice headwall (55 degrees) on approach to summit ridge</li><li>Spectacular high-altitude glacial approach from Chukung</li><li>Imja Lake — one of the world's most closely monitored glacial lakes</li><li>Commonly combined with EBC trek for ultimate 20-day Khumbu experience</li></ul>`,
