    name: "Kathesimbu Stupa",
    category: "STUPA",
    summary: "Kathesimbu Stupa is the most important Buddhist shrine in the Thamel district of Kathmandu, a 17th-century chaitya built as a replica of the sacred Swayambhunath Stupa to serve those unable to make the pilgrimage to the hilltop original. Set within a courtyard surrounded by smaller chaityas, votive offerings, and an ancient monastery, it is a living place of daily worship for local Newari Buddhists and a serene refuge from the busy lanes of Thamel just metres away. The name means 'Kathmandu Swayambhunath' in Newari.",
    story: `<p>Kathesimbu Stupa was built around 1650, during the height of the Malla dynasty's patronage of Buddhist architecture throughout the Kathmandu Valley. According to local tradition, the stupa was constructed from the leftover materials used in the renovation of Swayambhunath Stupa — a story that gives Kathesimbu a direct material connection to one of the most sacred sites in Vajrayana Buddhism. Its primary purpose was charitable and practical: the steep climb to Swayambhunath on its hilltop was difficult for the elderly, the infirm, and mothers with young children, so Kathesimbu was established as a proximate substitute where the same merit could be accumulated by a simple walk through the lanes of central Kathmandu. The all-seeing eyes of the Buddha, characteristic of Newari stupa design, are painted on the four faces of the harmika above the dome.</p><p>The stupa is technically classified as a monumental chaitya rather than a stupa — a distinction in Nepali Buddhist architecture relating to its form and the nature of the relics enshrined within it. It stands within a closed courtyard approached through narrow lanes south of Thamel, surrounded by a fascinating collection of smaller votive chaityas, ancient stone sculptures, metal relief panels, and inscriptions in Sanskrit and Newari scripts. The adjacent monastery, Sighahbaha, adds to the atmosphere of the complex and is home to a small community of monks and nuns who conduct daily rituals throughout the day. The courtyard functions as a neighbourhood gathering place — elderly women circling the stupa with prayer beads, children playing, monks engaged in quiet conversation.</p><p>For travellers staying in Thamel, Kathesimbu offers an easily overlooked but deeply rewarding pocket of authentic religious life amid the tourist commercial noise of the surrounding streets. The stupa is particularly animated in the early morning, when devotees begin their circumambulations before the shops open, and in the evening when butter lamps are lit at the niches surrounding the dome. It has survived multiple earthquakes, including the major 2015 Gorkha earthquake, with relatively minor damage — a testament to the skill of the medieval builders and the quality of the subsequent restorations. The stupa occupies a significant position in the Kathmandu Valley's Buddhist sacred geography, forming part of a network of shrines that together map the mandala of the valley floor.</p><ul><li>17th-century chaitya — replica of sacred Swayambhunath built from surplus materials</li><li>Living place of daily Newari Buddhist worship in central Thamel</li><li>Surrounding courtyard with ancient chaityas, stone sculptures, and inscriptions</li><li>Adjacent Sighahbaha monastery with resident monks and nuns</li><li>Serene refuge from the bustle of Thamel, just metres from tourist streets</li></ul>`,
